#import "template.typ": *

#let metadata = (
  title: "Straight and Level Flight",
  unit: "Group A (3-Axis) | Phase 1 — Lesson 2 | E3",
  author: "C.Moroney",
)

#let lesson = (
title: [Straight and Level Flight]

,aim: [
Fly the aircraft in a constant direction and at a constant altitude, at varying airspeeds and configurations, whilst maintaining balance and applying the PAT and LARI workcycles.
]

,overview: [
Building on the control skills from Lesson 1, the student now integrates all primary and ancillary controls into sustained straight and level flight. The PAT (Power, Attitude, Trim) workcycle is introduced for establishing performance, and the LARI (Lookout, Attitude, Reference, Instruments) workcycle for maintaining it. The student is introduced to the four forces of flight and basic altimetry. The instructor conducts the takeoff, then the student takes controls in the climbout to practice maintaining the climb attitude, continuing the progressive E8 (takeoff) handover.
]

,learning_outcomes: [
#text(size:12pt)[*Knowledge*]
- Recall the four aerodynamic forces (lift, weight, thrust, drag) and their importance in straight and level flight
- Explain lift generation and how angle of attack and airspeed affect lift
- Describe the concept of attitude flying: Power + Attitude = Performance
- Explain the PAT and LARI workcycles and when each is used
- Explain the altimeter subscale purpose and the QNH setting procedure
- Describe the difference between track and heading, and the role of the balance ball

#text(size:12pt)[*Skills*]
- Establish and maintain straight and level flight at cruise and slow cruise using the PAT workcycle
- Apply the LARI workcycle to detect and correct deviations in heading (±5°) and altitude (±150 ft)
- Set QNH and verify against aerodrome elevation or using AWIS/ATIS
- Maintain coordinated flight with ball centred ±1/4 width
- Trim accurately for hands-off level flight

#text(size:12pt)[*Non-Technical Skills*]
- [SA] Maintain lookout using the LARI workcycle; monitor instruments and airspace
- [TEM] Identify threats including wind drift, fixation, and traffic; verbalise threats when prompted
- [HF] Recognise parallax error in left-seat horizon referencing and correct for it
- [CRM] Apply correct control handover during the entire lesson
]

,theory_knowledge: [
- Human Factors — IMSAFE, TEM, SA, vision *(Pg 1, 3, 13–18)*
- Aerodynamics — aerofoils, lift, drag, thrust, relative airflow *(Pg 110-131, 154-155)*
- Aeroplane Performance — airspeed indicator, altimeter *(Pg 146-147, 73-74)*
- Air Legislation — VMC, right-of-way rules *(Pg 71-72)*
]

,ground_brief_topics: [
Total time: 40 minutes \
Equipment required: Aircraft model, access to electronic briefing, whiteboard \

*Non-Technical Skills* (5 minutes)
- [TEM] Threats: turbulence, fixation, traffic; errors: chasing the altimeter
- [SA] Systematic lookout (left, centre, right, above); clock code for reporting traffic
- [HF] Parallax correction in left seat; visual illusions in level flight

*Four Aerodynamic Forces and Lift* (10 minutes)
- Lift, weight, thrust, drag — equilibrium in level flight
- Coupling in the four forces and tail-down force
- Lift generation: angle of attack and airspeed
- Effect of flaps on lift and drag

*Attitude Flying* (10 minutes)
- Power + Attitude = Performance
- PAT workcycle: establishes a desired performance
- LARI workcycle: maintains a desired performance
- Normal cruise and slow cruise power settings for this aircraft

*Instrument Use and Altimeter* (10 minutes)
- QNH setting procedure; verify against aerodrome elevation
- Primary instruments for S&L: altimeter, VSI, ASI, balance ball
- Horizon is primary reference — instruments only _confirm_ performance
- LARI maintenance scan: Lookout — Attitude — Reference (distant point to maintain direction) — Instruments
]

,ground_tasks:[
#text(size:12pt)[*Instructor*]
- Review weather, NOTAMs, and maintenance release separately from student
- Demonstrate QNH setting on the ground
- Supervise pre-flight inspection with student; student to identify items checked

#text(size:12pt)[*Student*]
- Complete IMSAFE self-assessment and confirm fitness to fly
- Participate in pre-flight inspection and fuelling; begin to take the lead on documentation
- Set QNH under instructor guidance; verify against aerodrome elevation
- Continue developing taxiing technique
]

,in_flight_tasks:[
#text(size:12pt)[*E8 Takeoff Progression — Lesson 2*]
Instructor conducts takeoff and lift off. Student takes control during the initial climb — maintaining climbout heading on a reference point while instructor monitors.

#text(size:12pt)[*Demonstration*]
- S&L at normal cruise: establish with PAT, maintain _without_ reference to instruments
- Deviation and correction: demonstrate correcting back to straight and level attitude after deviations in pitch, roll and power
- S&L at normal cruise: now, introduce establishing with PAT and maintenance with LARI
- Slow cruise: transition using PAT, maintain with LARI
- Coordination: demonstrate ball movement and rudder correction

#text(size:12pt)[*Student Practice*]
- S&L at normal cruise: establish with PAT, maintain attitude _without_ reference to instruments
- S&L at normal cruise: correct back to S&L attitude after deviations (from instructor) in pitch, roll and power
- Using LARI workcycle, maintain:
  - Heading maintenance: hold ±5° using horizon and a distant ground reference point
  - Level flight: maintain ±150 ft using pitch/trim; crosscheck altimeter
  - Coordination: keep ball centred ±1/4 width
  - Slow cruise: transition using PAT; maintain with LARI
  - Deviation correction: recognise and correct heading and altitude deviations
- Scenario task: "Fly a steady heading toward the Gold Coast at normal cruise for 2 minutes, then transition to slow cruise maintaining altitude. Maintain for 2 minutes, then resume a normal cruise"
]

,common_errors:[
- *Chasing instruments*: Prioritise horizon attitude; glance at instruments to confirm.
- *Applying trim incorrectly*: Reinforce — if pushing forward, trim nose down #emph[with finger.]; if pulling back, trim nose up #emph[with thumb]. Build the habit early.
- *Uncoordinated flight*: Monitor reference point and ball if needed; apply rudder with aileron on heading corrections — "squeeze the ball."
- *Poor lookout*: Reinforce LARI.
]

,post_flight:[
- *Student Self-Assessment* (5 min): Student describes what went well and challenges faced.
- *Instructor Feedback* (5 min):
  - Evaluate against completion standards (P, S, C, or NC).
  - Highlight strengths and areas for improvement.
  - Discuss TEM/SA: "You corrected the heading deviation quickly — good LARI scan."
- *Scenario Reflection* (5 min): "How would incorrect QNH affect your altitude? How would you detect it?"
- *Next Steps*: Assign homework.
]

,standards_for_progression:[
#text(size:12pt)[*Progressing — may advance to Lesson 3*]
- *Straight flight*: Heading ±15° with minor prompting
- *Level flight*: Altitude ±300 ft, airspeed ±10 kts
- *Trim*: Applies trim in correct direction with minor guidance; approaching hands-off result
- *Deviation correction*: Recognises most deviations without prompting; correction within 20 seconds
- *QNH*: Sets altimeter correctly with one prompt
- *Coordination*: Ball displaced but student consistently aware and correcting without prompting
- *Airmanship*: Applies LARI workcycle with occasional reminders

#text(size:12pt)[*Solo Standard (S) — required before first solo*]
- *Straight flight*: Heading ±5° (S), smooth positive inputs
- *Level flight*: Altitude ±150 ft (S), airspeed ±10 kts (S)
- *Trim*: Can set and verify hands-off trim for cruise and slow cruise with some prompting
- *Deviation correction*: Recognises and corrects within 15 seconds
- *QNH*: Sets altimeter correctly with guidance
- *Coordination*: Ball ±1/4 width with prompting
- *Airmanship*: Applies LARI workcycle, maintains lookout, verbalises threats when prompted
- *Outcome*: Recorded in student records (P, S, C, or NC) with comments.
]

,safety:[
- *Weather*: Horizon clearly visible, ceiling \>2000 ft, surface wind \<25 knots
- *Altitude*: Conduct manoeuvres above 1500 ft AGL
- *Emergency Procedures*: Forced landing area pre-selected; instructor retains alert monitoring
- *TEM*:
  - Monitor for fixation on instruments at expense of lookout/attitude flying
  - Monitor traffic throughout; observe controlled airspace boundaries
  - Monitor for student anxiety or disorientation; pause, assess and continue or cut lesson short if needed
- *Aircraft Limits*: Avoid abrupt inputs, maintain attitude within upset limits
]

,homework:[
- Read Bob Tait's RAAus Study Guide:
  - Aerodynamics: Pages 110-131, 154-155 (forces, lift, drag, angle of attack)
  - Human Factors: Pages 1, 3, 13–18 (TEM, SA, IMSAFE, vision and scanning)
  - Aeroplane Performance: Pages 146-147, 73-74 (ASI, altimeter)
  - Air Legislation: Pages 71-72 (VMC requirements, right-of-way rules)
- Reflect on lesson:
  - "How would incorrect QNH affect your altitude reading?
  - How would turbulence make straight and level harder to maintain?"
]
)

